{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}} {{Infobox coat of arms |name = Emblem of Sri Lanka |image = Coat of arms of Sri Lanka.svg |image_width = 200 |middle = |middle_width = |middle_caption = |lesser = |lesser_width = |lesser_caption = |armiger = [[Sri Lanka|Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka]] |year_adopted = 1972 |crest = A [[Dharmachakra]] azure on a bezant |torse = |shield = On a circular shield: [[Maroon (color)|Maroon]], a lion [[Attitude (heraldry)#Passant|passant]] [[Or (heraldry)|Or]] bearing a Sri Lankan sword Or in its right forepaw; an [[orle (heraldry)|orle]] enhanced [[azure (heraldry)|azure]] bearing concentrically from the center outwards two [[Annulet (ring)|annulets]] [[argent]], the petals of a golden water lily proper, and an annulet Or; a [[bordure]] Or |supporters = Golden symbols of the [[Sun]] and the [[Moon]]; the stalks of rice growing from the vase surrounding the shield |compartment = A traditional grain vase |motto = |orders = |other_elements = An annulet Or passing under the crest and vase surrounding the stalks of rice; a bordure azure surrounding the entire arms |earlier_versions = |use = }}
The '''national emblem of [[Sri Lanka]]'''<ref>{{Citation |title = National Emblem |url = http://www.lankaembassy.jp/emblem.htm |accessdate = October 28, 2010 |publisher = Embassy of Sri Lanka to Japan |ref = |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://archive.is/20080513124608/http://www.lankaembassy.jp/emblem.htm |archivedate = 13 May 2008 |df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Citation |title = National Emblem |url = http://www.srilankaconsulatela.com/SriLankaCountryInformation.aspx |accessdate = October 28, 2010 |publisher = Sri Lankan Consulate in Los Angeles |ref = |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20101107004430/http://www.srilankaconsulatela.com/SriLankaCountryInformation.aspx |archivedate = 7 November 2010 |df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5f/Emblem_of_Sri_Lanka.svg/722px-Emblem_of_Sri_Lanka.svg.png|format=PNG|title=Photographic image of emblem|website=Upload.wikimedia.org|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> is used by the State of Sri Lanka and the [[Sri Lankan government]] in connection with the administration and government of the country. The current emblem has been in use since 1972.
The emblem features a gold lion [[Attitude (heraldry)#Passant|passant]], holding a sword in its right fore paw (the same lion from the [[flag of Sri Lanka]]) in the centre on a maroon background surrounded by golden petals of a [[Nelumbo nucifera|Blue Lotus]] the national flower of the country. This is placed on top of a traditional grain vase that sprouts sheaves of [[rice|rice grains]] that circle the border reflecting prosperity.
The [[crest (heraldry)|crest]] is the [[Dharmachakra]], symbolizing the country's foremost place for [[Buddhism]] and just rule. Traditional [[Sinhala people|Sinhalese]] heraldic symbols for the sun and the moon form the [[supporters]]. Sun and Moon, and Lion depicting Lord Buddha is given less prominence than cart wheel of English Buddhism, so it is in great discordance with National Scriptures.{{Citation needed|reason=Reliable source needed for the whole sentence|date=May 2017}}
==History== ===Portuguese period in Ceylon=== {{Main|Portuguese period in Ceylon}} The Portuguese had a coat of arms for their occupied territory in Sri Lanka, around 1505–1658. It has an Elephant in the foreground with palm trees around it and high mountains in the background.{{cn|date=December 2016}}
===Dutch period in Ceylon=== {{Main|Dutch period in Ceylon}} It is not known when the coat of arms for the Dutch occupied territory of Sri Lanka was adopted. The coat of arms is from a manuscript dating from 1717 to 1720. The arms is very similar to the previous Portuguese one with a modified design. It show the geography of the island with mountains and palm trees, with an elephant and cinnamon bales, and two small shields. The elephant is used because it is an animal used for work on the island and it symbolises strength. In front of the elephant are three bales of cinnamon, used for it was the main export product at the time, and the elephant holds a cinnamon branch in its trunk.<ref name="auto">{{cite web|url=http://www.ngw.nl/heraldrywiki/index.php?title=National_Emblem_of_Sri_Lanka |title=Sri Lanka - Ceylon |publisher=Ngw.nl |date= |accessdate=2012-08-17}}</ref>
===British Ceylon=== {{Main|British Ceylon}} Before independence, [[Ceylon]] used the [[coat of arms of the United Kingdom]] as the imperial emblem and a unique shield for the colony. This contained a [[Sri Lankan Elephant]] and Coconut trees and later a [[stupa]].
===Dominion of Ceylon=== {{Main|Dominion of Ceylon}} When Ceylon was granted [[Sri Lankan independence movement|independence]] from [[United Kingdom|Britain]] as a [[Dominion of Ceylon|dominion]] in 1948, the need of a new national emblem arose. A committee was named in order to create a national emblem. According to its recommendation a national emblem was adopted in 1954. The island had been a British Crown Colony since 1802. The emblem was not strictly in the heraldic tradition, however was granted by the College of Arms in 1954. It was derived from the Royal Banner of the [[Kandyan Kingdom]]. It largely reflected the Buddhist traditions of the [[Sinhalese people]]. At its center had a disk with a gold lion passant holding a sword (here called the Ceylon lion) in its right fore paw, on a maroon background, was taken from the Royal Banner of the [[Kandyan Kingdom]]. Around it were the golden petals of a water lily and topped with the crown ensigning the roundel is called the Ceylon crown; it follows the design of the crown worn by the [[kings of Kandy]]. The crown apparently symbolised Queen Elizabeth as Head of State of Ceylon, and it disappeared from the country's arms after change of status to a republic.<ref name="auto"/>
===Sri Lanka=== The present emblem of was created in 1972 with the ideas and guidance of [[Nissanka Wijeyeratne]].<ref>[http://www.rivira.lk/2009/01/04/rivinetha2.htm Amara Samara in Sinhala]. Rivira, Retrieved on 4 January 2009.</ref> At the time, he was Permanent Secretary to the Ministry of Cultural Affairs and Chairman of the National Emblem and Flag Design Committee. The designer of the emblem was [[Venerable]] [[Mapalagama Wipulasara Maha Thera]] <ref>{{si icon}} [http://www.lankadeepa.lk/Section/diyatha/01022009/07.htm ජනරජ ලාංඡනය නිර්මාණය කළ හැටි] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090608121821/http://www.lankadeepa.lk/Section/diyatha/01022009/07.htm |date=8 June 2009 }}. Sunday Lankadeepa, Retrieved on 1 February 2009.</ref><ref>[http://www.rivira.lk/2010/11/21/rivinetha2.htm Amara Samara in Sinhala]. Rivira, Retrieved on 21 November 2010.</ref> and Art Work by S.M Seneviratne.<!-- Reference in Sinhala: http://www.lankadeepa.lk/Section/diyatha/01022009/07.htm ( ජනරජ ලාංඡනය නිර්මාණය කළ හැටි . Sunday Lankadeepa, 1st February 2009 )--> The emblem features a gold lion passant, holding a sword in its right fore paw (the same lion from the [[flag of Sri Lanka]]) in the centre on a maroon background surrounded by golden petals of a [[Nelumbo nucifera|Blue Lotus]], the national flower of the country. This is placed on top of a traditional grain vase that sprouts sheaves of [[rice|rice grains]] that circle the border reflecting prosperity.
The [[crest (heraldry)|crest]] is the [[Dharmacakra]], symbolizing the country's foremost place for [[Buddhism]] and just rule.<ref>{{Citation |title = Our national symbols... |url = http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2010/01/31/jun05.asp |accessdate = October 28, 2010 |publisher = Sunday Observer, Sri Lanka's English Newspaper with the largest circulation |ref = |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100204215444/http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2010/01/31/jun05.asp |archivedate = 4 February 2010 |df = dmy-all }}</ref> Traditional [[Sinhala people|Sinhalese]] heraldic symbols for the sun and the moon form the [[supporters]].
